<subSubSection id="C3006505B5056661FF78FBF13F9573CF" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BA5368EB5056661FF78FBF13F9573CF" blockId="5.[136,1452,159,1767]" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis id="B96EEA9CB5056661FF78FBF13C3E73EB" bold="true" box="[189,312,1131,1155]" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Etymology</emphasis>
:—Honoring botanists Christopher and Sharon Davidson, who have supported botanical research and fieldwork by Missouri Botanical Garden in 
<collectingCountry id="F30D761EB5056661FD9EFB0A3F8973CF" box="[603,655,1168,1191]" name="Peru" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Peru</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3006505B5056661FF78FB293C4272AF" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BA5368EB5056661FF78FB293C4272AF" blockId="5.[136,1452,159,1767]" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis id="B96EEA9CB5056661FF78FB293C1173A3" bold="true" box="[189,279,1203,1227]" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Ecology</emphasis>
:—The new species is only known from two localities in 
<collectingCountry id="F30D761EB5056661FCBFFB2E3EA873A3" box="[890,942,1204,1227]" name="Peru" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Peru</collectingCountry>
. The first is the Yanachaga Chemillen National Park, near to Santa Barbara Peasant community, located in the buffer zone of the natural protected area, in the 
<collectingRegion id="49DEF86CB5056661FAD9FB4238AE7387" box="[1308,1448,1239,1263]" country="Peru" name="Pasco" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Pasco region</collectingRegion>
, Oxapampa province, Huancabamba in the central jungle of 
<collectingCountry id="F30D761EB5056661FCDEFB663E4A727B" box="[795,844,1276,1299]" name="Peru" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="13212A0BB5056661FC98FB613EB0727B" box="[861,950,1275,1299]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[216,1371,190,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[216,1371,190,1929]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution map of Epidendrum chrisii-sharoniae, A: Yanachaga Chemillen National Park, Pasco. B: Altomayo Protection Forest, San Martín, to North of Peru. Prepared by L. Valenzuela." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450815" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450815/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). The second one corresponds to Venceremos locality in the 
<collectingRegion id="49DEF86CB5056661FEE7FA853CE3725F" box="[290,485,1311,1335]" country="Peru" name="San Martin" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">San Martin region</collectingRegion>
in the North of 
<collectingCountry id="F30D761EB5056661FD57FABA3FC5725F" box="[658,707,1312,1335]" name="Peru" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="13212A0BB5056661FD14FA853E20725F" box="[721,806,1311,1335]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[216,1371,190,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[216,1371,190,1929]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution map of Epidendrum chrisii-sharoniae, A: Yanachaga Chemillen National Park, Pasco. B: Altomayo Protection Forest, San Martín, to North of Peru. Prepared by L. Valenzuela." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450815" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450815/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
). Only a few individuals were found forming small colonies on the branches of several tree species such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C1A4D0DB5056661FD66FAD93E997233" box="[675,927,1347,1371]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Escalloniaceae" genus="Escallonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Escalloniales" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="myrtilloides">
<emphasis id="B96EEA9CB5056661FD66FAD93E997233" box="[675,927,1347,1371]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Escallonia myrtilloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L.f. (in 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8B4B7FB5056661FBC1FAD939E57233" author="Linnaeus, C." box="[1028,1251,1347,1371]" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" refId="ref2852" refString="Linnaeus, C. (1782) Supplementum Plantarum SystematisVegetabilium. Orphanotrophe, Brunswig, 468 pp." type="book" year="1782">Linnaeus 1782: 756</bibRefCitation>
) (
<taxonomicName id="4C1A4D0DB5056661FB39FAD938A67233" box="[1276,1440,1347,1371]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Escalloniaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Escalloniales" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Escalloniaceae</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName id="4C1A4D0DB5056661FF4DFAFD3F497217" authority="Ruiz &amp; Pav. (1799: 42)" authorityName="Ruiz &amp; Pav." authorityPageNumber="42" authorityYear="1799" box="[136,591,1383,1407]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Saracha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="punctata">
<emphasis id="B96EEA9CB5056661FF4DFAFD3C417217" box="[136,327,1383,1407]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Saracha punctata</emphasis>
Ruiz &amp; Pav. (1799: 42)
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C1A4D0DB5056661FDA5FAFD3FDD7217" box="[608,731,1383,1407]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Solanaceae</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="4C1A4D0DB5056661FCDFFAFD39897217" authority="Brand (1901: 76)" authorityName="Brand" authorityPageNumber="76" authorityYear="1901" box="[794,1167,1383,1407]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Symplocaceae" genus="Symplocos" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nana">
<emphasis id="B96EEA9CB5056661FCDFFAFD3ECC7217" box="[794,970,1383,1407]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Symplocos nana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF8B4B7FB5056661FC16FAFD39897217" author="Brand, A." box="[979,1167,1383,1407]" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" pagination="76" refId="ref2214" refString="Brand, A. (1901) Symplocaceae mit 68 Einzenbildern in 9 Figuren IV. 242. In: Engler, H. G. A. Das Pflanzenreich. Regni vegetabilis conspectus. Im Auftrage der Konigl. preuss. Akademie der Wissenschaften / herausgegeben. Leipzig, pp. 76." type="book chapter" year="1901">Brand (1901: 76)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C1A4D0DB5056661FB5AFAFD38397217" box="[1183,1343,1383,1407]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Symplocaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Symplocaceae</taxonomicName>
), within a high montane sclerophyllous forest between 
<quantity id="4CE29B6BB5056661FDABFA113E0272CB" box="[622,772,1419,1443]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.85" metricValueMax="3.6" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" unit="m" value="2850.0" valueMax="3600.0" valueMin="2100.0">2100–3600 m</quantity>
elevation (
<figureCitation id="13212A0BB5056661FCBBFA113EB872CB" box="[894,958,1419,1443]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[136,229,1989,2011]" captionTargetBox="[158,1430,190,1965]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[158,1430,190,1965]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitat. A: High montane forest between 3200–3600 m; B: Sclerophyllous Forest on white sand; C: Characteristic tree species, Escallonia myrtilloides, whose twisted branches and trunks are home to epiphytic plants, including the new species; D: Flowering stems of Epidendrum chrisii-sharoniae (Photographs by L. Valenzuela)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450809" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450809/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). The species blooms between the months of July and October.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3006505B5056661FF78FA4939F2718F" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA5368EB5056661FF78FA4939F2718F" blockId="5.[136,1452,159,1767]" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">
<taxonomicName id="4C1A4D0DB5056661FF78FA493F077283" authorityName="L. Valenz. &amp; E. Santiago" authorityYear="2022" box="[189,513,1491,1515]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Epidendrum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chrisii-sharoniae">
<emphasis id="B96EEA9CB5056661FF78FA493F077283" box="[189,513,1491,1515]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Epidendrum chrisii-sharoniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the ‘Pergracile Group’ and the ‘Rhodoides Subgroup’ (Hágsater: 2004: pl. 730), which is characterized by the caespitose habit, the racemose inflorescence with narrow, parallel-sided spathes, the flowers with a wide, rounded mid-lobe and a large fleshy disc. The new species is recognized by the 4–8, oblong-lanceolate leaves, 2–3 spathes covering the whole length of the peduncle of the inflorescence, the flowers that are simultaneous, atropurpureous with the apices of sepals, clinandrium, anther, calli and disc of the lip yellowish-green, the sepals that are 
<quantity id="4CE29B6BB5056661FF4DF91D3DFB71F7" box="[136,253,1671,1695]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" unit="mm" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10–12 mm</quantity>
long, the petals 10–11 × 
<quantity id="4CE29B6BB5056661FDD8F91D3F9971F7" box="[541,671,1671,1695]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="0.7" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.6" valueMin="0.7">0.7–1.6 mm</quantity>
and linear-oblanceolate, the lip with the apex truncate, provided of an obovoid disc covering most of the mid-lobe (
<figureCitation id="13212A0BB5056661FDA0F9313FCB71AB" box="[613,717,1707,1731]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 2" captionStart-1="FIGURE 3" captionStartId-0="2.[136,229,1987,2009]" captionStartId-1="3.[136,229,1952,1974]" captionTargetBox-0="[215,1376,210,1954]" captionTargetBox-1="[192,1396,190,1928]" captionTargetId-0="figure-24@2.[193,1393,190,1963]" captionTargetId-1="figure-17@3.[192,1396,190,1928]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="3" captionText-0="FIGURE 2. Illustration of Epidendrum chrisii-sharoniae. A: Plant habit; B: Old flower, front view; C: Dissected perianth of young flower; D: Ovary and column, longitudinal section; E: Anther; F: Pollinia (Drawings by L. Valenzuela from the type)." captionText-1="FIGURE 3. Lankester Composite Digital Plate (LCDP) of Epidendrum chrisii-sharoniae. A: Plant habit; B: Inflorescence; C: Old flower, front, and side view; D: Dissected perianth of young flower; E: Ovary and column, longitudinal section; F: Anther (Photographs by L. Valenzuela from the type)." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450811" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450813" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6450811/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6450813/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Figs. 2–3</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C1A4D0DB5056661FD1AF9313EF271AB" authorityName="Hagsater" authorityYear="2004" box="[735,1012,1707,1731]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Epidendrum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cyclotylosum">
<emphasis id="B96EEA9CB5056661FD1AF9313EF271AB" box="[735,1012,1707,1731]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="168">Epidendrum cyclotylosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has 2–5, narrowly oblong-elliptic leaves, 2 spathes about half as long as the peduncle, and the petals are linear oblanceolate, 4.8–5.5 × 1.0– 
<quantity id="4CE29B6BB5056661FB59F95539F6718F" box="[1180,1264,1743,1767]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="168" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
